## Migration: `TimedExecutor` â†’ .NET 8

### Pattern Classification

Your code has two patterns:

| Pattern | Location | Replacement |
|---------|----------|-------------|
| **Timeout enforcement** | `thread.Abort()` after `Join` fails | `CancellationTokenSource.CancelAfter` |
| **ThreadAbortException control flow** | `catch (ThreadAbortException) { ResetAbort(); }` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |

### Why This Breaks on .NET 8

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` â€” the runtime cannot forcibly terminate a managed thread. `Thread.ResetAbort()` is also gone (`SYSLIB0006`). You must switch to **cooperative cancellation**.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        return ExecuteWithTimeout(
            token => work(),  // wrap legacy work
            timeout);
    }

    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        Task<T> task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw ex.InnerExceptions[0];
        }
    }
}
```

### Key Differences from the Original

| Aspect | .NET Framework (old) | .NET 8 (new) |
|--------|---------------------|--------------|
| Thread lifecycle | Manual `new Thread` + `Start` + `Join` | `Task.Run` (uses thread pool) |
| Timeout | `thread.Join(timeout)` then `Abort()` | `CancellationTokenSource(timeout)` |
| Abort mechanism | Preemptive â€” runtime injects exception | Cooperative â€” work must check token |
| Exception type | `ThreadAbortException` | `OperationCanceledException` |
| Cleanup | `ResetAbort()` | Not needed; cancellation doesn't auto-throw |
| Disposal | Nothing to dispose | `CancellationTokenSource` must be disposed |

### Critical Pitfall: Cooperative Cancellation Requires Cooperation

The `Func<T> work` overload wraps legacy code that **doesn't check the token**. This means:

> âš ď¸Ź After timeout, `TimeoutException` is thrown to the caller, but **the work keeps running on the thread pool** until it finishes naturally. There is no way to forcibly kill it in .NET 8.

To get true cancellation, callers must migrate to the `Func<CancellationToken, T>` overload and check the token:

```csharp
// âťŚ Old: uncooperative â€” work runs to completion even after timeout
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => ExpensiveCalculation(),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// âś… New: cooperative â€” work stops at checkpoints
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    token =>
    {
        foreach (var item in items)
        {
            token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
            Process(item);
        }
        return ComputeResult();
    },
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
```

### If Work Truly Cannot Cooperate

For third-party or native code that can't accept a token, move it to a **child process** and use `Process.Kill()`:

```csharp
// Last resort for uncooperative code
var process = Process.Start("worker.exe", args);
if (!process.WaitForExit(timeout))
{
    process.Kill(entireProcessTree: true);
    throw new TimeoutException("...");
}
```

### Checklist

- âś… No `Thread.Abort` / `ResetAbort` / `ThreadAbortException`
- âś… No `SYSLIB0006` warnings
- âś… `CancellationTokenSource` disposed via `using`
- âś… Timeout produces same `TimeoutException` as before
- âš ď¸Ź Audit all callers â€” migrate to the token-accepting overload for real cancellation
